field"><HandL fid="hlp"><Title fid="hl"><SectionName fid="se" index="field">US</SectionName><ColumnName fid="clm" index="field"></ColumnName><Headline fid="hd"><Para lang="en">What If Off-Duty Employees Unplugged? New measure being floated in the City Council would ban bosses from contacting workers after-hours</Para></Headline></Title><LeadPara fid="lp"><Para>New Yorkers are used to having their happy hours interrupted with emails or calls from the boss.</Para><Para>But a new proposal being floated in the City Council could give them the right to hit ignore.</Para></LeadPara></HandL><TailParas fid="td"><Para>A measure protecting private-sector employees from penalties for ignoring after-hours or weekend work communications is gaining steam among New York Democrats, while drawing concern from business groups.</Para><Para>Councilman Rafael Espinal (D., Brooklyn) introduced the bill in the New York City Council on Thursday, and state Sen. Diane Savino (D., Staten Island) is working on her own version to introduce in the state legislature.</Para><Para>"It's important for workers to be able to draw a line between their work lives and personal lives," said Mr. Espinal.</Para><Para>Mr. Espinal's legislation is modeled after the "Right to Disconnect" law that passed in France last year. His legislation would make it illegal for an employer with more than 10 workers to require employees to access their work-related communications outside of normal work hours. It would prohibit employers from taking action against employees for not responding. It doesn't apply to government workers.</Para><Para>Proponents says such a law would help labor regulations adapt to the smartphone era, when people's leisure and office hours are often blurred.</Para><Para>"The world of work is changing, and labor laws needs to change with it," Ms. Savino said.</Para><Para>Business groups said the council measure is too broad and expressed concerns it would hamstring employers and burden them with new regulations.</Para><Para>"I think they have to refine the industries this can be applied to," said Helena Natt, executive director of the Greater New York Chamber of Commerce. She pointed to industries like hospitality that call for unusual hours or on-the-fly labor.</Para><Para>Frank Kerbein of the Business Council of New York State, who opposes the idea, said full-time jobs "come with expectations of performance, and sometimes that is the expectation that there could be work outside the normal hours." He pointed to the perks and job securities that come with those jobs.</Para><Para>"At what point would employees be setting their hours worked instead of employers setting the terms and conditions of a job?" Mr. Kerbein asked.</Para><Para>The idea is still far from becoming law. New York Gov. Andrew Cuomo, New York City Mayor Bill de Blasio and City Council Speaker Corey Johnson declined to take a position on the bill Thursday.</Para><Para>New York state labor law already requires certain companies to pay hourly workers for any work conducted outside their usual hours. But employers have more jurisdiction over when they can ask salaried employees to be on the job.</Para><Para>Mr. Espinal, chairman of the City Council's Consumer Affairs Committee, said the city's Department of Consumer Affairs would be responsible for investigating and levying fines against employers who didn't comply with his bill.</Para><Para>He is planning a council hearing on the measure for this summer.</Para><Para>New York City labor lawyer Nicholas Sikon said the measure could also open new avenues for lawsuits for employees who have been fired. "It seems to be creating a new cause of action," he said, adding it might encourage employers to start setting clearer policies about when workers are expected to be on call.</Para><Para>Some of Mr. Espinal's fellow Democrats, however, expressed skepticism. "New York is the city that never sleeps," said Sen. Michael Gianaris, of Queens. "I'm not sure that this is in keeping with the culture."</Para><Para>Write to Mike Vilensky at <ELink type="webpage" ref="mailto:mike.vilensky@dowjones.com">mike.vilensky@dowjones.com</ELink></Para></TailParas><Byline fid="by" index="field">By Mike Vilensky </Byline><Credit fid="cr" index="field"></Credit><Contact fid="ct" index="field"></Contact><Notes fid="rf" index="field"></Notes><Art fid="art" index="field"></Art><Copyright fid="cy" index="field">Copyright 2018 Dow Jones &amp; Company, Inc. All Rights Reserved. </Copyright></Article></ArchiveDoc><AdocTOC adoctype="article"><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/ArchiveDoc::Article" type="arttext"></Item><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/InvertText" type="invtext"></Item><Item subtype="primary" size="0" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/what-if-off-duty-employees-unplugged-1521753474" type="webpage"></Item></AdocTOC></DistDoc>

